</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Arrgh, ok, I'm not playing EQ2 yet--no time!  no time!  And all my friends are in WoW!  But this walks into a philosophical argument I've been having with my husband about MMPORGs and this issue.
<br />

<br />
In EQ1, we were an enchanter/druid.  In our smallish circle of friends, we were the only healer and slower.  We'd log on and discover three friends sitting in PoK waiting because "They couldn't group without us."  Then when we had to log everyone would be like, "Well, we have to too, because without you we all die."  This was terribly frustrating and depressing, as you can imagine.
<br />

<br />
On the other hand, in WoW, as a priest and druid, so far I feel that no one needs us at all.  We come on and all of our friends are off soloing.  They gather up their alts to group with us, but it really feels like they're just humouring us:  "How quaint, they still like to group."  Now, I'm really happy that they find it easy to solo without us, because I don't have to feel required--yes, it was wearying.  On the other hand, I miss bringing something to the table beyond my sparkling personality--that alone isn't going to get people to group with me through 60 levels.   <img src="images/smiles/icon_eek.gif" alt="Shocked" border="0" />  
<br />

<br />
I don't really want to compare games specifically here (it's become clear that that's not an argument that ever gets anywhere), I'm just curious--do people think it's better to be too necessary or not necessary at all?  (Yes, the ideal would be in the middle, but let's assume for the sake of argument a game has to err on one side or the other).<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://home.att.ne.jp/apple/dmolden/screenshots/pixcol.gif" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=611032" target="_blank" class="postlink">Columbyne Celebfin</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
