			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm really starting to notice the stuns and stifles make. I actually play twice a week at a RL friends' house. When we are taking rather hard mobs I say out loud "stunning" or "silencing" a few times on the first few fights when I do so. Then I purposely skip the stun on the next mob and tell them "sorry, that one was my fault, I missed my stun" The tank learns to associate his bar being orange and red more often without me there, the cleric learns that they're going to have to heal a bit more. I hear them say "we can't do this one until you get here" allot now. 
<br />

<br />
The problem is, if you don't have a regular enchanter in your group, and if you don't know what the spells look like and do, you're less likely to catch on to why we are useful. I'm not one to spam group chat with "stunning %T, please oooh and ahhh now", but in some way you have to make the group aware of what you are actually doing for them. That is the difficult part.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
